cal abuse or phishing activity\n\n Balance security requirements with deliverability concerns, considering:\n\n   -  Legitimate email services and senders that may be affected by strict policies\n\n   -  Potential impact on email deliverability and reputation\n\n\nStep 4: Determine the Optimal DMARC Policy\n\n\n Based on the analysis, determine the optimal DMARC policy for each subdomain, considering:\n\n   -  None  monitoring only \n\n   -  Reject  rejecting unauthenticated emails \n\n   -  Quarantine  quarantining unauthenticated emails \n\n   -  Reject with percentage  rejecting a percentage of unauthenticated emails \n\n Consider a gradual implementation approach, starting with monitoring  p=none  and gradually increasing the policy strength as needed\n\n\nStep 5: Implement and Monitor DMARC\n\n\n Implement the chosen DMARC policy for each subdomain, using the relevant DNS records  TXT or XML \n\n Monitor DMARC reports to track authentication results, identify potential issues, and adjust the policy as needed\n\n Utilize DMARC analytics tools to gain insights into email authentication and potential abuse\n\n\nTools and Methods to Aid in DMARC Policy Determination\n\n\n DMARC analytics tools, such as:\n\n   -  DMARC Analyzer\n\n   -  Agari\n\n   -  Dmarcian\n\n Email authentication testing tools, such as:\n\n   -  Sender Policy Framework  SPF  testing tools  e. g. SPF Wizard, SPF Validator \n\n   -  DomainKeys Identified Mail  DKIM  testing tools  e. g. DKIM Validator, DKIM Wizard \n\n Email flow visualization and analysis tools, such as:\n\n   -  Email flow diagrams and mapping tools  e. g. Lucidchart, Draw. io \n\n   -  Email log analysis tools  e. g. Loggly, Splunk \n\n\nBy following this step-by-step approach and leveraging the recommended tools and methods, domain owners can determine the optimal DMARC policy for their domain with multiple subdomains, balancing security with deliverability and ensuring the authenticity and trustworthiness of their emails. '}